{{Refimprove|date=June 2010}} {{Infobox video game | title = G.I. Joe: The Atlantis Factor | image = G.I. Joe The Atlantis Factor Cover.jpg | caption = Box cover | developer = [[KID]] | publisher = [[Capcom|Capcom U.S.A.]] | series = ''[[G.I. Joe]]'' | released = {{vgrelease|NA|March 1992<ref name="GameFAQs">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamefaqs.com/nes/587292-gi-joe-the-atlantis-factor |title=G.I. Joe: The Atlantis Factor for NES |publisher=GameFAQs |date= |accessdate=2012-09-17}}</ref>}} | genre = [[Action game|2D action]] [[platform game|platformer]] | modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]] | platforms = [[Nintendo Entertainment System|NES]] }}
'''''G.I. Joe: The Atlantis Factor''''' is the title of a [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] [[video game]] developed by [[KID]] and published by [[Capcom]] in the United States in 1992. Previously, a ''[[G.I. Joe (NES video game)|G.I. Joe]]'' video game was released for the NES by [[Taxan]] in 1991.
==Storyline== Having survived the last time he fought the G.I. Joe Team, [[Cobra Commander]] has raised the ancient island of [[Atlantis]] from the ocean depths and is using it as a base. With a nearly indestructible army and powerful space weapons, the power-crazed Cobra is plotting to use the long lost powers of the Atlanteans in their bid to rule the world.<ref name="GameFAQs"/>
==Gameplay== The game's format is similar to that of Capcom's ''[[Bionic Commando (arcade)|Bionic Commando]]'' series, with an overhead map of the various stages. In order to progress, the player must navigate the map and clear each sub-stage leading up to one of several Cobra bases. Once in a base, the player must fight through hostile Cobra forces and also complete a secondary mission (such as rescuing hostages, setting bombs, or locating a key item). Each base stage concludes with a battle against a Cobra leader ([[Overkill (G.I. Joe)|Overkill]], [[Cesspool (G.I. Joe)|Cesspool]], [[Firefly (G.I. Joe)|Firefly]], [[Major Bludd]], [[Destro]], and Cobra Commander).
There are several playable characters in the game: [[Hawk (G.I. Joe)|General Hawk]], [[Roadblock (G.I. Joe)|Roadblock]], [[Wet Suit (G.I. Joe)|Wet Suit]], [[Snake Eyes (G.I. Joe)|Snake Eyes]], [[Storm Shadow (G.I. Joe)|Storm Shadow]], and [[Duke (G.I. Joe)|Duke]].<ref name="yojoe">{{cite web| url = http://www.yojoe.com/archive/games/atlantis.shtml| title = G.I. Joe: The Atlantis Factor for the NES| last = Roberts| first = Matt| publisher = YoJoe.com| accessdate = 2010-06-17}}</ref> At the beginning of the game, the player can only use Hawk, and must unlock the other characters one by one by completing other stages.<ref name="mobygames">[http://www.mobygames.com/game/gi-joe-the-atlantis-factor- G.I. Joe: The Atlantis Factor] at [[MobyGames]]</ref> Once players have discovered a character, they can "decide" which characters will come with them, and alternate between them during gameplay by pressing the “pause” button and accessing the pause menu. Each character has their own agility, stamina and strength rating, although they are not shown unlike the [[G.I. Joe (video game)|previous game]].<ref name="allgame">{{cite web| url = http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=14984| title = G.I. Joe: The Atlantis Factor - Overview| last = Weiss| first = Brett Alan| publisher = [[Allgame]]| accessdate = 2010-06-17}}</ref>
In addition to the playable characters, [[Gung-Ho (G.I. Joe)|Gung-Ho]], [[Spirit (G.I. Joe)|Spirit]], and [[Big Bear (G.I. Joe)|Big Bear]] can be summoned to support the player by refilling life or weapon ammunition, though they must first be rescued by completing certain sub-stages. [[Stalker (G.I. Joe)|Stalker]] also appears but only in cutscenes, as he coordinates the mission from the G.I. Joe base.<ref name="yojoe"/>
