{{Infobox serial killer | name=Gary Ray Bowles | image=Gary Ray Bowles.jpg | image_size=170px | birth_date={{Birth date and age|1962|01|25}} | birth_place=[[Clifton Forge, Virginia]] | death_date= | death_place= | cause= | victims=6-25 | country=United States | states=[[Florida]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[Maryland]] | beginyear=1994 | endyear=1994 | apprehended=October 22, 1995 | conviction= {{ubl|[[Sexual assault]]|Unarmed [[robbery]]|[[Murder]]}} | sentence=[[Capital punishment|Death]] }}
'''Gary Ray Bowles''' (born January 25, 1962) is an American [[serial killer]] who was sentenced to death for the murder of six men.
==Early life==
Bowles was born in [[Clifton Forge, Virginia]], and was raised in [[Rupert, West Virginia]]. His father, "Frank" who worked as a coal miner, had died from [[Coalworker's pneumoconiosis|Black Lung Disease]] six months before, and his mother, Frances remarried several times. Bowles was [[child abuse|abused]] by his second stepfather, a violent [[alcoholic]] who also abused Bowles' mother and older brother. The abuse continued until, at the age of 13, Bowles fought back and severely injured his stepfather. He left home soon after, angered by his mother's decision to remain in the marriage.<ref name="trutv">{{cite web | last = Bell | first = Rachel | title = Gary Ray Bowles | work = truTV Crime Library | publisher = | url = http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/serial_killers/predators/gary_bowles/index.html | accessdate = 4 April 2012}}</ref>{{rp|2}} He was [[homeless]] for the next few years, earning money as a [[male prostitution|prostitute]].<ref name="trutv" />{{rp|2}}
In 1982, he was arrested for beating and [[sexual assault|sexually assaulting]] his girlfriend, and was sentenced to six years in prison. In 1991, after his release from prison, he was convicted of unarmed robbery in the theft of an elderly woman's purse, a crime for which he was sentenced to four more years in prison; he was released in two.<ref name="findarticles.com">[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m2194/is_n12_v63/ai_16548140/ "Gary Ray Bowles - murder suspect - VICAP Alert"] ''Law Enforcement Bulletin'' December 1994.</ref>
==Murders== On April 14, 1994, in [[Daytona Beach, Florida]], Bowles killed his first known victim, John Hardy Roberts, who had offered him a temporary place to live. Bowles beat and strangled him to death, and then stole his [[credit card]]. Police soon considered him a suspect after finding his [[fingerprint]]s and [[probation]] records at the crime scene.<ref name="trutv" />{{rp|4}} Over the next six months, Bowles murdered five other men in [[Nassau County, Florida]], [[Jacksonville, Florida]], [[Savannah, Georgia]], [[Atlanta, Georgia]], and [[Wheaton–Glenmont, Maryland|Wheaton]], [[Montgomery County, Maryland|Montgomery County]], [[Maryland]]. His typical ''[[modus operandi]]'' was to prostitute himself to his victims before beating and strangling them, and stealing their credit cards.<ref name="findarticles.com"/> While on the run, Bowles was put on the [[FBI]]'s [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives|list of the country's 10 Most Wanted Fugitives]] for his four known victims.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prisonboundserialkillers.com/gary_bowles |accessdate=January 25, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091202033351/http://www.prisonboundserialkillers.com/gary_bowles |archivedate=December 2, 2009 }}</ref> Finally, on October 22, 1994, Bowles was arrested for the murder of Walter Jamelle "Jay" Hinton, and confessed to all six murders.<ref name="trutv" />
==Trial== Bowles was found guilty of three counts of murder and [[death penalty|sentenced to death]], but the sentence was reversed by the [[Florida Supreme Court]]. He was given a new sentencing hearing, and again received the death penalty.<ref>{{cite web | title = (Unofficial Transcript of oral argument before the Florida Supreme Court) Gary Ray Bowles vs State of Florida | work = | publisher = WFSU | date = | url = http://www.wfsu.org/gavel2gavel/transcript/96732.htm | accessdate = 4 April 2012}}</ref> Bowles is held in [[Union Correctional Institution]] awaiting execution.
