'''George Eliot''' was an [[English people|English]] [[espionage|spy]] in the reign of Queen [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]].
Eliot is reported to have been an unsavoury character. He earned his living as a [[confidence trick]]ster, but was well known as a [[rapist]] and suspected of being a [[murder]]er.<ref name=rbhaec>{{cite web |url=http://www.berkshirehistory.com/articles/campion_lyford.html |title=The Arrest of St. Edmund Campion |author=Ford, David Nash |year=2011 |work=Royal Berkshire History |publisher=Nash Ford Publishing |accessdate=22 January 2011}}</ref> He entered the service of [[Robert Dudley, 1st Earl of Leicester]] as a spy to avoid a charge of the last crime and agreed to seek out [[recusancy|recusant]] Catholics and hand them over to the authorities.<ref name=rbhaec/>
At [[Lyford, Oxfordshire|Lyford]] Grange in [[Berkshire]] (now [[Oxfordshire]]), he tracked down the [[Jesuit]] priest, [[Edmund Campion]].<ref name=rbhaec/> After calling for a magistrate from [[Abingdon, Oxfordshire|Abingdon]] with re-inforcements, he arrested him and sent him to London for trial and execution.<ref name=rbhaec/>
