'''George Henry Lamson''' (8 September 1852 – 28 April 1882) was an American doctor and murderer.
In his early career he had been a volunteer surgeon in [[Romania]] and [[Serbia]], and decorated for his work. He returned to England and practised in [[Bournemouth]]. He became addicted to [[morphine]] and his financial situation grew desperate.
In 1881 he visited his 18-year-old brother-in-law Percy John, a [[hemiplegia|hemiplegic]], at his boarding school and gave him a slice of [[Dundee cake]]. He also gave him a capsule from a batch that were later tested and found to contain the poison [[aconitine]], as recorded in the case history at Old Bailey Online.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/features/8361106.The_American_doctor__war_hero__drug_addict_and_murderer_who_lived_among_us/ |title=The American doctor, war hero, drug addict and murderer who lived among us |first=Stephen |last=Bailey |newspaper=Bournemouth Echo |date=31 August 2010 |accessdate=9 July 2011}}</ref>
Lamson was tried in March 1882 with [[Montagu Williams]] acting for his defence: he was found guilty of murdering Percy in order to secure a share of the family inheritance. He had poisoned his victim with [[aconitine]] in the cake, a substance which Lamson had learnt about from Professor [[Robert Christison]] in university. Christison had taught that aconitine was undetectable but forensic science had improved since Lamson's student days.<ref>{{cite book|last=Macinnis|first=Peter|title=It's true!: you eat poison every day|series=It's true|volume=18|publisher=Allen & Unwin|year=2006|isbn=1-74114-626-7|pages=80–81}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Macinnis|first=Peter|title=Poisons: from hemlock to Botox and the killer bean of Calabar|publisher=Arcade Publishing|year=2005|isbn=1-55970-761-5|pages=25–26}}</ref><ref>Parry & Wright (2000) p.103</ref>
Lamson's execution was delayed when word came that his family and friends in the United States requested time to send proof of insanity in the doctor's family and in his own life. The evidence was sent but was not sufficient to reduce the sentence.{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}}
Lamson was hanged by [[William Marwood]] at [[Wandsworth Prison]] on 28 April 1882.<ref>{{cite book | title=The hangmen of England: how they hanged and whom they hanged : the life story of "Jack Ketch" through two centuries | author=Horace Bleackley | publisher=Taylor & Francis | year=1929 | isbn=0-7158-1184-3 | page=245 }}</ref>
