{{Infobox criminal | name = Goran Vuković | birth_date = 1959 | birth_place = [[Belgrade]], [[People's Republic of Serbia|PR Serbia]], [[Federal People's Republic of Yugoslavia|FPR Yugoslavia]] | death_date = 12 December 1994 (aged 35) | death_place = Belgrade, [[Republic of Serbia (1990–2006)|Serbia]], [[Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|FR Yugoslavia]] | alias = "Majmun" ("Monkey") | occupation = Gangster }}
{{moresources|date=March 2016}}
'''Goran "Majmun" Vuković''' (1959 – 12 December 1994) was a [[Serbia]]n [[gangster]] who earned his nickname ''Majmun'' ('Monkey') due to his unique style of breaking into buildings: climbing and jumping balconies to enter a premises.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/info/vesti/index.php?yyyy=2012&mm=05&dd=05&nav_category=12&nav_id=606692|title=Kako kriminalci dobijaju nadimke|trans_title=How criminals got their nicknames|publisher=B92|date=5 May 2012}}</ref>
Although he spent a considerable amount of time in [[Germany]], he is regarded as a member of the Voždovac gang.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.novosti.rs/dodatni_sadrzaj/clanci.119.html:275867-Fama-zvana-Vozdovac|title=Fama zvana Voždovac|trans_title=Fame called "Voždovac"|publisher=Večernje Novosti|date=17 July 2002}}</ref> He garnered notoriety in the killing of mobster [[Ljubomir Magaš]] (aka Ljuba Zemunac) in [[Frankfurt]], [[West Germany]] on 10 November 1986, in front of the local courthouse.
Magaš was unofficially proclaimed as the [[Capo di tutti capi|godfather]] of Serbian [[organized crime]] at the time. Vuković received a prison sentence of 5 years for the crime. He later returned to Belgrade.<ref name=Vreme>{{cite web|url=http://www.vreme.com/cms/view.php?id=1060098|title=Eksplozivno leto i posledice|last=Švarm|first=Filip|publisher=[[Vreme]]|date=28 June 2012|language=Serbian}}</ref>
After returning to Belgrade in 1991, he survived five assassination attempts.<ref name=Vreme/> Such attempts included the bombing of his car as well as two policemen trying to kill him.{{cn|date=March 2016}} Due to this, he concluded that the Serbian secret police had a hit-list, and that Romeo Savić was murdered by said police. The reason for Savić's assassination (according to Vuković) is because Savić was openly talking about police drug dealers. Vuković was mentioned in [[Ratko Mladić]]'s personal diaries. Mladić wrote that Vuković and Duško Malović were involved in the 1994 murder of Serbian reporter [[Dada Vujasinović|Radislava Vujasinović]].{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}
When he got back to Belgrade, he survived five murder attempts before getting murdered in December 1994.<!-- by whom? --> He was shot in his car near the [[Yugoslav Drama Theater]] building by three masked assassins, who appeared out of darkness of nearby [[Manjež]] park and opened continuous fire from automatic weapons. Vuković and his bodyguard Duško Malović were found dead.<ref name=Vreme/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kurir.rs/crna-hronika/gospodari-podzemlja-7-cuvenih-srpskih-kriminalaca-devedesetih-clanak-1928825|title=Masters of the underground: 7 most famous Serbian criminals of the 1990s|publisher=Kurir|date=12 September 2015}}</ref>
